commentBody:
Stuck on MNEME? Don't be ashamed, she's so obscure, she doesn't get mentioned, by name, in either Grimal or Graves! She does appear (or so I hear) in the work of that Fodor of the 2nd century, Pausanias (who admits that the lore was even then obscure and obsolete), and that eminent historian of Ancient Greese, Fικιπαίδεια.
(The base root, connected with the Greek word for "memory," and the Latin one for "mind," is pretty easy to suss out.)

@Sam Lyons already addressed LOTUS, below, but I'll have to concur, it does seem to weaken the theme. But then, sometimes it's hard to see the FEN for the lilies.

@Paul

I got the trick when I got the revealer, about ¾ way through the puzzle. Went back and looked at the tree-adjacent and "tree" themers, and figured out that the missing letters spelled out FOREST in order top to bottom, L to R.

I admit it was a nice Thursday trick.

@Puzzlemucker

The "privileges" of being older with a fairly good memory (my wife would sometimes say it's selective, though).

I remembered seeing SCHWEPPES in ads many times, and didn't have any trouble with its spelling. ISOSCELES was mostly filled in with crosses, so turned out to be easy, and I've heard enough about Brazil over the years that São PAULO was an instant fill-in. I did have other problems, though…

@Larry  the delay from black and white to color was obviously about money…certainly the cameras cost more…But there was a secondary issue with shows already in production. To get a good black and white image for people at home the costumes and sets and makeup weren’t black and white.  They were an array of weird colors designed to look good when filmed in black and white.

And then when they got to color there were issues that the studio lights would cause costumes and such to show up wrong to the home viewer.  One of the regularly commented issues with this is Kirk’s uniform color on Star Trek.  Sometimes it was green.  Sometimes gold.   


There were also issues when they switched from standard definition to high definition broadcasts.   All of the sets for things like news shows and morning shows had to be rebuilt.  They had been originally built for low def.  In high def you could see all of the flaws and scuff marks and everything which was imperfect in those old sets.

@Francis

LL Cool J was rapping four decades ago.

So in 1987 would you have been complaining about references to Elvis Presley?

@Francis
Sounds like complaining to me, but …anyway.
Time goes by, things change, and we aren’t always in tune with absolutely everything absolutely all the time. Whatever the reason, don’t let the crossword puzzle get you down.

@Sebastian

Come one.  You know one of the goals of hip-hop/rap is to come up with catchy names by using clever, phonetic sets of letters, like Big Boi and Lil Nas X.

I don't think it's "pompous" to point out the absolutely obvious.

@NobodyThree
@Mick

Thanks for understanding what I was saying.  It was a bit of a wave goodbye as I ride into the sunset.

I didn't expect to encounter so much push back.

@Ann

Oops. I should have read the clue. I assumed it said 1988, not 1998. 

Yep, it’s wrong. Someone confused two songs released 10 years apart.

@Beth

Great. Emus ate my reply to you. 

Bottom line: symmetry is tradition for NYT grids. If it doesn't make sense, it's gotta be tradition, eh?

@Andrzej

Yes. The U.S. has had some terrible traditions that some are trying to revert back to. 

But regarding the puzzle... thank you. I had wondered if there was something functionally important about symmetry. It's funny that it would be required for aesthetic reasons, because I personally enjoy asymmetry in art, whether visual or musical. To me, too much symmetry is boring.

@Barry Ancona

Oh no, those were put on pause for Poland. 

Wait... what's that? Oh, my sources inform me they've been reinstated. Never mind.

@Patrick J

I don't believe that ANY crossword anywhere uses diacritics.

For a while the big whoop here was about the Spanish word for "year", which when used without the tilde describes an important but unmentionable body part. Lately, "year" has been clued as the Portuguese term, which is the same as that unmentionable Spanish word but which only translates back to "year".

@Andrzej     Bruno Mars owns some bars, and he also sings bars.  "Bars" is another word for measures, because a black bar separates one from another.  

SST is SuperSonic Transport, a plane that flies faster than the speed of sound.  It was retired in 2003.  The US puts the month first, then the date.

You had a third question that I can't see when typing this reply.

@Mike
Always glad to linden ear when you give us something from your larch collection of puns.

I could say I pine for them but that would be acorny comment.

@Mike

Puns are made by fools like me,
But only a Scot can make a tweed.

@Al  in Pittsburgh
Al, your poetry selections tend to break my heart. This one did (with a little help from The Guardian <a href="https://tinyurl.com/555m6c4n" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/555m6c4n</a>). 

Is it your birthday again?

@Francis

To have an infinite coastline you'd need infinite molecules to measure.

For a nerdy head explosion, check out the paradox of Gabriel's Horn on YouTube.

@Steve L

Then you have the problem of how you manage to use the wheel when the wheel is very much larger than the size of the nooks and crannies you're trying to measure.

You can't make the wheel follow every single zig and zag of the actual coastline.

@Mr Dave

No, not really.

Of course the whole thing breaks down at the atomic level anyway.  But it would be relatively easy to find infinite pathways through a collection of atoms.

@Elizabeth Connors - when I was approved to receive the earned doctorate in my field, my major teacher pulled me aside and looked me in the eye:
“Davey my boy, don’t you ever let me hear you call yourself ‘Doctor’ unless you are reserving a table or calling a cab.”
The NYT seems to follow the same sort of guidelines.

@David Connell
location, location: you might rmember, I moved from NE OH to MI: In Cleveland, no one was every referred to, by themselves or by other, as "Doctor," unless they were a MD/DO/DDS. (In a choral group I sang with, a young, undergraduate soprano once exclaimed, "I can't believe I'm singing with my professor, Dr. R-g!" Dr. R-g? She was just "Lisa" to us!)

Here in Detroit, everyone with an advanced graduate degree is referred to as "Dr. X" or "Dr. Y." How pompous!

@Times Rita

Like me, you must print the standard version vs. the newspaper version.  In spite of trying, I can't figure out how to print the newspaper version without using a ton of toner.  I already have my settings on draft mode, but it still comes out very dark. Other outlets let me easily adjust the ink, and I wish the NYT would do the same.

Since it's likely that no programming changes will be made to the standard version, I've resigned myself to the fact that I will miss out on some of the fun.

@Ms. Billie M. Spaight
You could google this yourself, but I decided to and found this right away
“ there are numerous crossword puzzle creators with disabilities who have successfully crafted and published puzzles, demonstrating the accessibility and inclusivity of the craft. Examples include Will Shortz, who recovered from strokes and continued to edit the New York Times crossword.”

@Steve L

Apparently so...or they just want to see how many hoops we'll jump through.

(I always have to close Comments if I should want to see the Key, but I admit I seldom read the columns. TLDR)

@Nick
That was interesting. Thanks for the link. 

Maryland is crazy. 31 miles of ocean coastline. But 3100 miles of you include the ‘inlet’ (Chesapeake bay).

@Paul  "If people want to know every word before they attempt a puzzle they should try the Wordsearch"  LOL, that is just too funny!! I love that line.

But you're right that some puzzles are easier than expected, some are harder.  A few just wow the socks off me with their brilliance, while sometimes one doesn't impress me at all. But that's how it goes. They're all good.

I'm currently trying to reach a 1 year streak of solves. I think I can do it,I hope I can do it.  But if not, that's okay. I'll just start again at zero. I'm enjoying the challenge of my goal. As you say, it's about the journey.

@Ami you can get to your year.  The secret is...on those impossible days...Those days where you wonder how anyone can get more than 2 words...Those days where you stare at a mostly full grid and wonder where your life has gone wrong...

*pause*  

take a breath.... watch some tv... take a walk...   When you get back to it...perhaps that impossible to divine keystone becomes obvious and you solve that last bit lickety-split.

@pat in oregon

Silas Marner? 

George, not T. S., although I didn't remember that, myself.

@Mick i would think so on some level there are groupings of love or hate of the puzzle.

The other day....we saw a European uprising when there were too many Americanisms in the puzzle. I thought it was very interesting how many must be lurking on the board and felt the need to comment a couple of days ago.

I almost felt bad for them....almost.

@Bill

When I want to get to the comments quickly, I opened the new york times in my browser on my android phone and then go to games, word play and then comments.

And sometimes I will leave that tab open, and as somebody else said, just hit refresh when I go back in.

@Bill

I'm another one here who is so addicted to Wordplay, that I will check back throughout the day, to watch the replies and the reccos accumulate. Not every day, but frequently.
(But I work through the browser on my desktop, so none of those phone app problems.)

