@Momerlyn, et al
MINI wants to be in all caps as well, despite not being an abbreviation for anything. I won't bore you with the long history of Morris Mini Minors, or what makes it a Cooper or not, but understand that I have way too much knowledge on the subject.

Long story short: you can build a LEGO MINI Cooper.

@Oikofuge

I meant to say publishers have different rules for different initialisms, though it's also true, to a lesser extent, for acronyms.
Miles per hour, for instance, is much more commonly rendered "mph" than "MPH".

@Oikofuge

The difference there is that no one has registered mph as a name. Did you know that zipper used to be a name? But it drifted into common use because it was not a protected trademark. Then it was too late. Kleenex has a clever letter they send out to remind people to use it as a trademark...something to the effect of "for using Kleenex blah blah blah, Kimberly-Clark says 'bless you.'" They've used it as an ad as well. The Xerox company had a tough time trying to get people to photocopy their documents instead of Xeroxing them, but I think they are finally winning that battle.

I'm so glad I'm not part of that kind of team. I never did enjoy ulcers.

